'''Tidal downsizing''' is a hypothetical mechanism for the formation of [[planets]].<ref name="Wilkins_2011">{{cite web|last1=Wilkins|first1=Alasdair|title=Why Earth might have started out as a gas giant|url=http://phys.org/news/2011-09-rocky-planets-born-gas-giants.html|publisher=[[Gizmodo]]|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="Redd_2011">{{cite web|last1=Redd|first1=Nola Taylor|title=Rocky planets could have been born as gas giants|url=http://phys.org/news/2011-09-rocky-planets-born-gas-giants.html|publisher=[[Phys.org]]|accessdate=6 June 2016}}</ref> The process begins with the formation of large clumps of gas, of roughly 10 [[Jupiter]] masses, via [[gravitational instability]] in the outer parts of the [[protoplanetary disk]]. The clumps migrate inward due to gravitational interactions with the gas disk. Solid grains within the clump collide and grow and settle toward the center forming a [[planetary core|massive core]]. The clump is disrupted due to [[tide|tidal forces]] or heating from the [[star]] when it approaches within a few [[astronomical unit|AU]] of the star leaving behind a smaller object. Depending on the extent and timing of the mass loss the remnant may be a [[terrestrial planet]], an [[ice giant]] or a [[gas giant]].<ref name=Nayaksin_2010>{{cite journal|last1=Nayakshin|first1=Sergie|title=Formation of planets by tidal downsizing of giant planet embryos|journal=Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society Letters |date=2010|volume=408|issue=1|page=L36-l40|doi=10.1111/j.1745-3933.2010.00923.x|arxiv=1007.4159|url=http://mnrasl.oxfordjournals.org/content/408/1/L36|bibcode = 2010MNRAS.408L..36N }}</ref>
==References== {{Reflist}}
[[Category:Astronomy]]

{{expert needed|1=Astronomy|date=June 2017}} '''Cosmic wind''' is a powerful [[Cosmos|cosmic]] force that can push interstellar dust clouds of low density into intergalactic [[Outer space|space]]. Although it easily pushes low density gas and dust clouds, it can not easily push high density clouds. As the cosmic winds start to push the clouds, they start to separate and start looking like taffy being pulled apart.<ref name="Yale">{{Cite web|url=https://news.yale.edu/2015/07/27/dust-pillars-destruction-reveal-impact-cosmic-wind-galaxy-evolution|title=Dust pillars of destruction reveal impact of cosmic wind on galaxy evolution|last=Shelton|first=Jim|date=July 27, 2015|website=YaleNews|access-date=December 31, 2017}}</ref> It has a primary composition of [[photon]]s ejected from large stars and sometimes [[thermal energy]] from [[Supernova|exploding stars]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://science.time.com/2012/09/06/blowhard-galaxies-and-the-great-cosmic-wind/|title=Blowhard Galaxies and the Great Cosmic Wind|last=Cray|first=Daniel|newspaper=Time|access-date=2016-09-28|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> It can be caused by orbital motion of gas in the cluster of a [[galaxy]],<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.astronomy.com/news/2015/07/new-hubble-image-shows-cosmic-wind-creating-pillars-of-destruction|title=New Hubble image shows cosmic wind creating "Pillars of Destruction" {{!}} Astronomy.com|access-date=2016-09-28}}</ref> or can be ejected from a [[black hole]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.space.com/4494-black-holes-launch-powerful-cosmic-winds.html|title=Black Holes Launch Powerful Cosmic Winds|access-date=2016-09-28}}</ref> Because new stars and planets form from gases, the cosmic winds that push the gases away are preventing new stars from forming.<ref name="Yale"/>
