In [[astronomy]], the '''Goldreich-Kylafis''' (GK) effect causes certain molecular line emission to be weakly [[Linear polarization|linearly polarized]], e.g., in the presence of a [[magnetic field]]. More specifically it is predicted that interstellar [[Spectral line|spectral lines]] possess a few percent linear polarization provided that the [[Optical depth (astrophysics)|optical depth]] in the source region is both [[Anisotropy|anisotropic]] and of order unity and the [[Spontaneous emission|radiative rates]] are at least comparable to the collision rates.  Compared to polarized dust emission, the GK effect has the potential to yield additional information along the line of sight through its dependence on velocity in the line profile.<ref>{{Cite journal|arxiv=0810.2844 |title=[0810.2844&#93; Observations of the Goldreich-Kylafis effect in star-forming regions with XPOL at the IRAM 30m telescope |journal=Astronomy & Astrophysics |volume=492 |issue=3 |pages=757 |date=2008-10-16 |last1=Forbrich |first1=Jan |last2=Wiesemeyer |first2=Helmut |last3=Thum |first3=Clemens |last4=Belloche |first4=Arnaud |last5=Menten |first5=Karl M |doi=10.1051/0004-6361:200811056 |bibcode=2008A&A...492..757F }}</ref>

The theoretical background of the work was published by [[Peter Goldreich]] and - his postdoc at the time - [http://www.physics.uoc.gr/en/faculty/n.kylafis Nick Kylafis]  in a series of two papers in [[The Astrophysical Journal]] in [https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1981ApJ...243L..75G/abstract 1981] and [https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1982ApJ...253..606G/abstract 1982]

