The following [[Outline (list)|outline]] is provided as an overview of and topical guide to astronomy:
'''[[Astronomy]]''' &ndash; studies the [[universe]] beyond Earth, including its [[physical cosmology|formation and development]], and the evolution, [[physics]], [[chemistry]], [[meteorology]], and [[motion (physics)|motion]] of [[Astronomical object|celestial objects]] (such as [[galaxy|galaxies]], [[planet]]s, etc.) and [[Phenomenon|phenomena]] that originate outside the [[atmosphere of Earth]] (such as the [[Cosmic microwave background radiation|cosmic background radiation]]).
{{TOC limit|limit=2}}
==Nature of astronomy== Astronomy can be described as all the following:
* An [[academic discipline]]: one with academic departments, curricula and degrees; national and international societies; and specialized journals. * A scientific field (a branch of [[science]]) &ndash; widely recognized category of specialized expertise within science, and typically embodies it ** A [[natural science]] &ndash; one that seeks to elucidate the rules that govern the [[nature|natural]] world using [[Empirical method|empirical]] and [[scientific method]]s. *** A branch or field of [[space science]] * A [[Amateur astronomy|hobby or part-time pursuit]] for the satisfaction of personal [[curiosity]] or appreciation of [[beauty]], the latter especially including [[astrophotography]].
==Branches of astronomy== * [[Astrobiology]] &ndash; studies the advent and [[evolution]] of [[biological system]]s in the universe. * [[Astrophysics]] &ndash; branch of [[astronomy]] that deals with the [[physics]] of the [[universe]], including the physical properties of [[astronomical object|celestial object]]s, as well as their interactions and behavior.<ref>{{cite web | title=astrophysics | publisher=Merriam-Webster, Incorporated | url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/astrophysics | accessdate=2011-05-22 }}</ref> Among the objects studied are [[galaxy|galaxies]], [[star]]s, [[planet]]s, [[exoplanet]]s, the [[interstellar medium]] and the [[cosmic microwave background]]; and the properties examined include [[luminosity]], [[density]], [[temperature]], and [[chemistry|chemical]] composition. The subdisciplines of theoretical astrophysics are: ** [[Compact objects]] &ndash; this subdiscipline studies very dense matter in [[white dwarf]]s and [[neutron star]]s and their effects on environments including [[accretion (astrophysics)|accretion]]. ** [[Physical cosmology]] &ndash; origin and evolution of the universe as a whole. The study of cosmology is theoretical astrophysics at its largest scale. ** [[Computational astrophysics]] &ndash; The study of astrophysics using computational methods and tools to develop computational models. ** [[Galactic astronomy]] &ndash; deals with the structure and components of our galaxy and of other galaxies. ** [[High energy astrophysics]] &ndash; studies phenomena occurring at high energies including [[active galactic nuclei]], [[supernova]]e, [[gamma-ray burst]]s, [[quasar]]s, and [[Bow shock|shock]]s. ** [[Interstellar astrophysics]] &ndash; study of the [[interstellar medium]], [[intergalactic medium]] and [[cosmic dust|dust]]. ** [[Extragalactic astronomy]] &ndash; study of objects (mainly galaxies) outside our galaxy, including [[Galaxy formation and evolution]]. ** [[Astronomy#Stellar astronomy|Stellar astronomy]] &ndash; concerned with [[Star formation]], physical properties, [[main sequence]] life span, [[variable star|variability]], [[stellar evolution]] and extinction. ** [[Plasma astrophysics]] &ndash; studies properties of [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]] in outer space. ** [[Relativistic astrophysics]] &ndash; studies effects of [[special relativity]] and [[general relativity]] in astrophysical contexts including [[gravitational waves]], [[gravitational lens]]ing and [[black hole]]s. ** [[Solar physics]] &ndash; Sun and its interaction with the remainder of the Solar System and interstellar space. * [[Planetary Science]] &ndash; study of planets, moons, and planetary systems. ** [[Atmospheric science]] &ndash; study of atmospheres and weather. ** [[Exoplanetology]] &ndash; various planets outside of the Solar System ** [[Planetary formation]] &ndash; formation of planets and moons in the context of the [[formation and evolution of the Solar System]]. ** [[Planetary rings]] &ndash; dynamics, stability, and composition of planetary rings ** [[Magnetosphere]]s &ndash; magnetic fields of planets and moons ** [[Planetary surface]]s &ndash; surface geology of planets and moons ** [[Planetary interiors]] &ndash; interior composition of planets and moons ** [[Small Solar System bodies]] &ndash; smallest gravitationally bound bodies, including [[asteroid]]s, [[comet]]s, and [[Kuiper belt object]]s. * Astronomy divided by general technique used for astronomical research: ** [[Astrometry]] &ndash; study of the position of objects in the sky and their changes of position. Defines the system of coordinates used and the [[kinematics]] of objects in our galaxy. ** [[Observational astronomy]] &ndash; practice of observing celestial objects by using telescopes and other astronomical apparatus. It is concerned with recording data. The subdisciplines of [[observational astronomy]] are generally made by the specifications of the detectors: *** [[Radio astronomy]] &ndash; Above 300&nbsp;µm *** [[Submillimetre astronomy]] &ndash; 200&nbsp;µm to 1&nbsp;mm *** [[Infrared astronomy]] &ndash; 0.7–350&nbsp;µm *** [[Optical astronomy]] &ndash; 380–750&nbsp;nm *** [[Ultraviolet astronomy]] &ndash; 10–320&nbsp;nm *** [[X-ray astronomy]] &ndash; 0.01–10&nbsp;nm *** [[Gamma-ray astronomy]] &ndash; Below 0.01&nbsp;nm *** [[Cosmic ray astronomy]] &ndash; [[Cosmic ray]]s, including plasma *** [[Neutrino astronomy]] &ndash; [[Neutrino]]s *** [[Gravitational wave astronomy]] &ndash; [[Graviton]]s ** [[Photometry (astronomy)|Photometry]] &ndash; study of how bright celestial objects are when passed through different filters ** [[Spectroscopy]] &ndash; study of the spectra of astronomical objects * Other disciplines that may be considered part of astronomy: ** [[Archaeoastronomy]] ** [[Astrochemistry]]
